title: Lynnville-Sully wins regular-season finale
text:
Published: Friday, Oct. 16, 2015 10:46 a.m. CDT • Updated: Friday, Oct. 16, 2015 12:08 p.m. CDT Caption (Jocelyn Sheets/Daily News) Lynnville-Sully’s Carson Fisk sets the ball for a teammate in a home match earlier this season. The Hawks won Thursday on the road at North English. By Jocelyn Sheets Newton Daily News 
NORTH ENGLISH — Breaking a two-match skid and building momentum going into the postseason, Lynnville-Sully’s Hawks defeated host English Valleys in four sets Thursday. 
Lynnville-Sully won its final regular-season match, 25-13, 23-25, 25-15, 25-18. 
“In the second set, English Valleys came alive and we struggled on serve receive,” Hawk head coach Heather James said. “The team stayed focused to win the last two sets.” 
Brenna Lanser delivered 15 kills and nine digs for the Hawks. Makenzy Rozendaal pounded down 11 kills and made 14 digs. Lataya Meyer had seven kills and nine digs. 
Kristen Van Der Wilt went 18-of-18 at the service line with five ace serves. She had 10 digs in the match. Carson Fisk put up 17 set assists. 
With the victory, the Hawks finished 7-4 in South Iowa Cedar League volleyball action and 10-8 overall in the regular season. Lynnville-Sully turns its focus to Class 1A Region 5 play. 
The Hawks travel to Marengo Tuesday to play seventh-ranked Iowa Valley, which won the SICL championship. The first-round match begins at 7 p.m. 
The winner advances to the second round of the regional against the winner of the Belle Plaine and Montezuma match. That match will be at 7 p.m. Oct. 27 at Marengo. 
Lynnville-Sully lost to Iowa Valley in SICL action Monday, 25-13, 25-13, 25-7. Lanser had five kills and Meyer downed four kills. Fisk put up six set assists. Rozendaal made 12 digs and Van Der Wilt made 10 digs. 
The Hawks dropped a four-set match to Sigourney on Oct. 8. Sigourney beat Lynnville-Sully 20-25, 25-14, 25-19, 25-19. Lanser, the SICL leader in digs, was credited with 34 digs against the Savages. She delivered 15 kills in the match. 
Lynnville-Sully had 99 digs as a team with Shelby Foster with 17, Vander Wilt with 15 and Camryn Russell with 11 digs. Fisk had 11 set assists. 
Lanser had 297 digs going into Thursday’s match at English Valleys. She was fifth in kills, 186, in the conference.
